Big O notation, or Big Omega notation for short, is a mathematical tool used to describe the complexity of an algorithm. It describes how much time and space the algorithm requires as its size increases.
The idea is to express the running time of an algorithm in terms of a function that measures the amount of work done by the algorithm as it runs:
O(f(n)) = f(n) * constant + o(f(n)), where f(n) is the running time and o(f(n)) represents a term that becomes negligible compared to f(n) when n approaches infinity (i.e., the algorithm's running time grows at a slower rate than f(n)).

